<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101351800494922></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101351800494922><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=101351800494922>some tips</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=101351800494922#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=122815><span id= >ScottKatahn</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>8 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Feb 12th 7:46 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I was in a group last night at orc2 on Saryrn and was amazed that I was grouped with wizards who I needed to train.&nbsp;&nbsp;Figuring that this phenomenon is not exclusive to EC and Saryrn I would like to share some tips for effective wizarding in groups.<br><br>1) Wait for the tanks to tag the mob and bring it back to camp before nuking.  Patience is a virtue here because a mistake on your part will bring the mob howling down on you.  You are not a tank, you do NOT have the ac or hps to take an accidental aggro and stand a good chance of being dead before the tanks can taunt it off.<br><br>2) Don't overburn.  In most routine situations the tanks can probably handle the fight.  As a wizard you are there in case things go south in a hurry.  Toss in the occasional lower-level nuke to help soften it up, and maybe a mid-level nuke to finish it off quickly when running, but outside of emergencies that should be it.  Without mana all we are is an xp sponge, remember that.<br><br>3) If there is no enchanter in your group, or other form of crowd control, AOE spells are very useful in multi-mob scenarios - with certain guidelines.  Target the main mob, the one your primary tank is fighting.  Wait a tick or two for it to get good and mad at him, and then drop your AOE spell on that mob.  Because of the way the hate list works, as long as you don't aggro the main mob, you won't aggro *any* of them.  (There were at least 4 occassions last night where that little trick saved my group from a blowout.  Weakened mobs can get dropped faster and you get to be the hero.  This is probably the best reason to not overburn and be OOM when your group needs you.)<br><br>4.) With the AOE spells, be very careful about their area of effect and where non-aggro'd mobs are.  I learned this the hard way in EC because those blasted snakes are everywhere and it cost me a couple of times.  Also when fighting at the orc camps, you need to be careful of Altunic walking buy at an inopportune moment and getting caught in your oh-so-flashy AOE nuke.  <br><br>5.) If a mob aggro's on you, hold still.  Don't cast. Don't attack. DON'T RUN!  Spam the chat channel that you are aggro'd and let the tanks taunt it off you.  Casting is likely to get interrupted, wasting mana, although if you can get a root off then you could try it.  Fighting is nearly useless, we don't melee and every bit of damage you do makes it harder for the tank to get it off you.  If you run, you make it nearly impossible for the tanks to hit it while it is still quite effectively reducing you to paste.  (Trust me guys, my main is a 31 SK and I have lost count of the number of casters who have died while screaming &quot;getitoff getitoff!&quot; and running - I let them die because trying to get it off them is impossible with them moving whereas if they hold still I will move heaven and earth to get it off them because I can.)<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Kadia Coldnight<br>Dark Elven Shadow Knight<br><br>Xviin<br>Dark Elven Wizard in service to no god<br><br>Zarros<br>High Elven Cleric of Tunare<br><br>Saryrn Server</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
